Let's Get Coffee's Fall 2019 round is in full swing - join us in making Cornell a more connected community! Sign up as either a new student (freshman or transfer!) or upperclassman at https://tinyurl.com/lgc2019 by Friday, September 27 @ 11:59 PM.

----

Let's Get Coffee seeks to help resolve the perennial question of how to best transition freshmen and transfer students into college life at Cornell University. Our goal at Let’s Get Coffee is to connect new students to upperclassmen with similar interests to provide guidance, create connections, and ultimately strengthen the Cornell community.

event: Democracy, Today: Fake News, Social Networks, and Algorithms
location: Thu 4:30 PM · The Alice Statler Auditorium · Ithaca, New York
URL: Democracy, Today: Fake News, Social Networks, and Algorithms
description:
The annual Cornell Center for Social Sciences' Distinguished Lecture in the Social Sciences speaker David Lazer is a Distinguished Professor of Political Science and Computer and Information Science, Northeastern University, and co-director for the NULab for Texts, Maps, and Networks. This free, public lecture is also sponsored by the departments of Communication, Computer Science, and Information Science. Following his lecture, there will be a public reception in the Statler Hotel Carrier Ballroom.

Democracy, Today: Fake News, Social Networks, and Algorithms

The Internet is increasingly the home of democracy. It is where people turn for civic information, engage in political discourse public and private, and turn to mobilize collectively. The virtual structures of the Internet are, in some ways, quite distinct from what preceded; and in other ways, they reproduce and amplify those pre-existing patterns. The Internet can be the ultimate disseminator of misinformation; as well as the ultimate educator. People have at their fingertips more diverse sources of information than ever before; yet many of the institutions for the production of political and civic information are being eviscerated. This talk will discuss the informational and social logics of the Internet-- what is our democracy, today?-- how they support and undermine democracy, and concludes with a discussion of what structures and practices we need from the Internet to support democracy, today.

Professor Lazer's research focuses on the nexus of network science, computational social science, and collaborative intelligence. He is the founder of the citizen science website Volunteer Science and the political visualization website VisPolics. His research has been published in such journals as Science, Proceedings of the National Academy of Science, the American Political Science Review, and the Administrative Science Quarterly, and has received extensive coverage in the media, including the New York Times, NPR, the Washington Post, the Wall Street Journal, and CBS Evening News.

Professor Lazer serves in multiple leadership and editorial positions, including as a board member for the International Network of Social Network Analysts (INSNA), reviewing editor for Science, associate editor of Social Networks and Network Science, numerous other editorial boards and program committees. He was a founder of the Political Networks Section, as well as a founder and founding host of the Political Networks conference.

event: 1st People’s Festival: International Year Of Indigenous Language
location: Sat 11:30 AM · Dewitt Park · Ithaca, New York
URL: 1st People’s Festival: International Year Of Indigenous Language
description:
The First Peoples’ Festival is scheduled for Saturday, September 28, 2019 at Dewitt Park from 11:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. and will be in partnership with the Apple Harvest Festival.

The First Peoples’ Festival honors the history and culture of first peoples of this land and all of their ancestors. It also recognizes that we all have a common bond as human beings alive today. In 2019, as our theme for the festival, we are excited to honor the International Year of Indigenous Languages. We will be showcasing the diversity of Indigenous Languages that exist in Tompkins County. As always, the First Peoples’ festival offers an opportunity to have our communities learn about indigenous issues from an indigenous perspective. We look forward to continue our collective commitment to justice, peace, and sovereignty and we hope you will join us in honoring indigenous people, cultures, and histories.

We plan to bring together various indigenous vendors, foods, performances, cultural demonstrations, family friendly activities, and community resource booths, which will provide our community with an opportunity to experience an amazing cultural and educational event free and accessible to all. This year we are also featuring Mohawk artist and activist Dioganhdih.

location: Today 5 PM · Klarman Hall, Cornell University · Ithaca, New York
description:
Jeremy Scahill will deliver the 2019 Kops Freedom of the Press lecture.

Scahill is one of the three founding editors of The Intercept. He is an investigative reporter, war correspondent, and author of the international best-selling books, Dirty Wars: The World Is a Battlefield and Blackwater: The Rise of the World’s Most Powerful Mercenary Army. He has reported from Afghanistan, Iraq, Somalia, Yemen, Nigeria, the former Yugoslavia, and elsewhere across the globe. Scahill has served as the national security correspondent for The Nation and Democracy Now!.

Scahill’s work has sparked several congressional investigations and won some of journalism’s highest honors. He was twice awarded the prestigious George Polk Award, in 1998 for foreign reporting and in 2008 for Blackwater. Scahill is a producer and writer of the award-winning film “Dirty Wars,” which premiered at the 2013 Sundance Film Festival and was nominated for an Academy Award.

This event is free & open to all.

description:
Cornell Concert Commission, along with Alumni Affairs and Development, presents the Cornell University 2019 Homecoming Concert with Saint Motel and Daya! 

Tickets on sale at CornellTickets.com NOW

Saint Motel, widely known for electrifying live performances and turning simple concerts into incredible audiovisual spectacles, are indie pop superstars. With a stage presence like few others, they've played alongside Arctic Monkeys, Weezer, Panic! at the Disco, and even done legendary sets on Coachella's main stage. Joining them is Grammy award-winning singer and songwriter, Daya. Breaking out of suburban Pennsylvania, Daya has burst onto the scene in just 5 short years with bop after chart-topping bop! Currently on tour with MARINA, formerly Marina and the Diamonds, Daya's personal brand of mesmerizing trance pop is bold, empowering, and irresistibly fun, making it no surprise her song "Don't Let Me Down" won both Best Dance Recording and Best Dance Track in 2017.
 
Catch these two amazing performers back to back, Saturday, October 5th at Cornell University's Barton Hall! 

Visit CornellTickets.com and follow us @CornellConcerts on FB, IG, or Twitter for more updates!

location: Thu 10 AM · Downtown Ithaca · Ithaca, New York
description:
The Winter Lights Festival, presented by Tompkins Trust Company, will features a modern lights palace called Prismatica throughout the center of Downtown Ithaca from December 5-15. 

Prismatica is an interactive installation comprising 25 pivoting prisms more than six feet tall. Visitors will be able to view all the colors of the rainbow, touch the prisms, and hear bell music as they rotate them.  

After sunset, the enormous interactive kaleidoscope's illusory effects reach a crescendo.

This Winter Light Festival event features a number of unique events during the 10 day exhibit:

December Gallery Night

A Silent Disco on Friday, December 6, featured as a part of our Downtown Ithaca Gallery Night tour. Grab a pair of headphones and dance the night away at our outdoor disco!

Chowder Cook-off, presented by Maguire Hyundai Subaru, features over 30 chowders in a variety of style, offered by restaurants from all over Ithaca. Come taste them all and vote for your favorite!

Santa’s Arrival, presented by Maguire Hyundai Subaru, is a perfect opportunity to ring in the holiday season. Santa and his elves enter Downtown Ithaca is the most unique way possible: repelling down from the top of Center Ithaca! Enjoy festive music and have your photo taken with Santa at this free family event. 

Visit downtownithaca.com for more a list of all the family-friendly events being offered during this festival.

Prismatica is an installation created by RAW Design in collaboration with ATOMIC3, produced by Quartier des Spectacles Partnership of Montreal, Canada.
